# GUARDRAILS --- MANDATORY PRE-FLIGHT & IN-FLIGHT CHECKS

Upload this document alongside SHORT_PROMPT.docx,
ANTI_HALLUCINATION.docx, PERSONA.docx, and RESEARCH_INTENSITY.docx. This
document takes HIGHEST PRIORITY when any conflict exists between
governing documents.

## SECTION 1 --- DOCUMENT HIERARCHY (WHICH RULES WIN)

**When multiple governing documents are uploaded, apply this priority
order:\
**

PRIORITY 1 (HIGHEST): GUARDRAILS.docx (this document)

PRIORITY 2: ANTI_HALLUCINATION.docx

PRIORITY 3: RESEARCH_INTENSITY.docx (run-specific configuration)

PRIORITY 4: PERSONA.docx

PRIORITY 5: SHORT_PROMPT.docx (master template)

**RULE:** If RESEARCH_INTENSITY.docx specifies a NARROWER scope than
SHORT_PROMPT.docx (e.g., fewer soil types, fewer regions, fewer
management levels), the NARROWER scope in RESEARCH_INTENSITY wins.
SHORT_PROMPT.docx is the master template showing ALL POSSIBLE options.
RESEARCH_INTENSITY.docx is the RUN-SPECIFIC configuration showing WHAT
TO ACTUALLY DO THIS RUN.

## SECTION 2 --- MANDATORY DOCUMENT RECONCILIATION (STEP 0)

**BEFORE any research, table building, or data work, you MUST:\
**

2.1 Read ALL uploaded governing documents completely.

2.2 Compare the SOIL TYPE lists across all documents. If they differ,
use the RESEARCH_INTENSITY.docx list (narrower scope wins).

2.3 Compare the REGION lists across all documents. Same rule ---
narrower wins.

2.4 Compare the PLANTATION TYPE / MANAGEMENT lists. Same rule.

2.5 Compare the CLIMATE ZONE lists. Same rule.

2.6 If ANY conflict is found between documents, you MUST:

a\) List the conflict explicitly to the user.

b\) State which document takes priority per Section 1.

c\) Ask the user to confirm before proceeding.

2.7 You MUST NOT proceed past Step 0 until all document conflicts are
resolved.

## SECTION 3 --- CONFIGURATION LOCK (STEP 0.5)

**After document reconciliation, you MUST print a CONFIGURATION LOCK
SUMMARY and get user approval before any work begins.\
**

The CONFIGURATION LOCK SUMMARY must contain:

MATERIAL: \[exact material name\]

REGION(S): \[list only those specified in RESEARCH_INTENSITY\]

SOIL TYPE(S): \[list only those specified in RESEARCH_INTENSITY\]

PLANTATION TYPE(S): \[list only those specified\]

CLIMATE ZONE(S): \[list only those specified\]

WORKFLOW STAGES: \[which stages\]

TABLES TO BUILD: \[A, B, C, D --- which ones\]

GOVERNING DOCUMENTS: \[list all uploaded docs and their priority\]

**RULE:** You MUST NOT include any soil type, region, plantation type,
or climate zone that is NOT explicitly listed in the
RESEARCH_INTENSITY.docx configuration. The SHORT_PROMPT.docx master list
shows what is POSSIBLE, not what is ACTIVE for this run.

**SCOPE LOCK:** Once the user approves the Configuration Lock, NO
additional soils, regions, or management scenarios may be added during
table building. If during research you discover data for a soil/region
not in the locked configuration, you MUST note it as \"OUT OF SCOPE ---
available for future run\" and NOT include it in any table.

## SECTION 4 --- CITATION BLOCKLIST (BANNED PHRASES)

**The following phrases are NEVER acceptable as citations or references
in any table, note, or text. If you cannot find a real source, use
\"DATA GAP\" instead.\
**

BANNED: \"Industry data\"

BANNED: \"Industry benchmarks\"

BANNED: \"Industry reports\"

BANNED: \"Industry estimates\"

BANNED: \"Corporate sustainability reports\" (without specific company,
year, title)

BANNED: \"Company data\"

BANNED: \"Mill records\"

BANNED: \"PTPN reports\" (without specific PTPN number, year, title)

BANNED: \"Soil surveys\" (without specific survey name, year, author)

BANNED: \"Field observations\"

BANNED: \"Field data\"

BANNED: \"Local data\"

BANNED: \"ScienceDirect \[year\]\" (without authors, title, journal,
volume, pages)

BANNED: \"Google Scholar\"

BANNED: \"Research papers\"

BANNED: \"Literature\"

BANNED: \"Various sources\"

BANNED: \"Estimated\"

BANNED: \"Proportional estimate\"

BANNED: \"Calculated estimate\"

BANNED: \"Peat hydrology\" or any topic name used as if it were a
reference

BANNED: \"BPS statistics\" (without specific publication title, year,
URL)

BANNED: Any URL without author, year, title, and access date

BANNED: Any wiki-style source (Wikipedia, Akvopedia, etc.) as a PRIMARY
source

BANNED: \"Personal communication\" (without named person, institution,
date)

**RULE:** If you catch yourself writing any phrase from this blocklist,
STOP and replace it with either a real citation (Author, Year, Title,
Journal) or \"DATA GAP --- no peer-reviewed source found\".

## SECTION 5 --- ESTIMATE = DATA GAP (NO EXCEPTIONS)

**Any value that is estimated, projected, proportionally scaled,
interpolated, or extrapolated from other data MUST be tagged as DATA
GAP.\
**

5.1 The word \"Estimated\" in any Method or Notes column = DATA GAP.

5.2 The phrase \"Proportional estimate\" = DATA GAP.

5.3 Values derived by scaling from one region/soil to another = DATA
GAP.

5.4 Values derived by applying a ratio from a different material = DATA
GAP.

5.5 The ONLY acceptable non-DATA-GAP derivations are:

a\) Standard stoichiometric conversions (P→P₂O₅, K→K₂O, N→CP)

b\) Standard analytical derivations (NDF-ADF=Hemicellulose,
ADF-ADL=Cellulose)

c\) Values calculated from measured inputs using published formulas
(e.g., Dulong HHV)

These derivations MUST show the calculation and cite the formula source.

## SECTION 6 --- SCOPE CREEP PREVENTION

6.1 Before adding ANY row to any table (D1, D2, D3, Summary), check:

\"Is this soil/region/management level in my CONFIGURATION LOCK?\"

If NO → Do not add the row. Note it as \"Available data exists for \[X\]
--- out of scope this run.\"

6.2 Before adding ANY scenario column, check:

\"Is this scenario based on a soil/region/management in my CONFIGURATION
LOCK?\"

If NO → Do not add the scenario.

6.3 PEAT / HISTOSOL SPECIFIC RULE:

**If Peat / Histosol is NOT in the RESEARCH_INTENSITY soil list, you
MUST NOT:**

a\) Include peat regions (Riau peat, Jambi peat, C. Kalimantan peat) in
any table.

b\) Include peat soil chemistry sections.

c\) Apply peat-specific C:N ratios, decomposition rates, or emission
factors.

d\) You MAY add a single note: \"Peat data available --- not in scope
for this run.\"

## SECTION 7 --- INTERNAL CONSISTENCY GATE (BEFORE DELIVERY)

Before delivering ANY workbook, you MUST verify:

7.1 CROSS-SHEET CONSISTENCY:

Every value that appears in more than one sheet (e.g., C:N in D1, BSF,
and Summary) MUST be identical or explicitly explained if different.

Run a manual cross-check: pick 5 parameters that appear in multiple
sheets and verify they match.

7.2 ANALYTICAL METHOD CONSISTENCY:

If two values come from different analytical methods (e.g., Van Soest vs
Wise chlorite), you MUST:

a\) Label each value with its method.

b\) Add a note explaining why they differ.

c\) NEVER present values from different methods as if they should sum or
be directly compared.

7.3 TABLE COMPLETENESS CHECK:

The prompt requires Tables A, B, C, D. Before delivery, confirm:

\[ \] Table A exists and has: CHNS-O, ash, minerals, energy

\[ \] Table B exists and has: Proximate, fiber, nutritional, BSF columns

\[ \] Table C exists and has: Agronomic values, oxide conversions,
replacement values

\[ \] Table D exists and has: Carbon scenarios, IPCC factors, credits

\[ \] Source Registry Table exists

\[ \] Weighted Calculation Examples (≥10 parameters)

\[ \] Quality Summary Dashboard

\[ \] Mathematical Verification Checks

\[ \] Conflict Resolution Log

If ANY of these is missing, the workbook is INCOMPLETE --- do not
deliver without flagging.

## SECTION 8 --- MANDATORY SELF-AUDIT (FINAL STEP)

After building the workbook but BEFORE delivering to the user:

8.1 Pick 3 random citations from the workbook. For each one, verify:

a\) It has Authors, Year, Title, Journal/Publisher.

b\) It is NOT on the Citation Blocklist (Section 4).

c\) The value attributed to it is plausible for the material.

8.2 Pick 3 random numeric values. For each one, verify:

a\) It appears in the correct unit and basis (DM vs as-received).

b\) If it appears in multiple sheets, it is consistent.

c\) It is not tagged \"Estimated\" without being marked DATA GAP.

8.3 Check the CONFIGURATION LOCK against every D-table row:

a\) Every soil in D tables is in the Configuration Lock.

b\) Every region in D tables is in the Configuration Lock.

c\) No out-of-scope items have crept in.
